For fucks sake I was such an upbeat person, what happened.…?

(I know what happened)

Dann kommen wir zum sehr komplizierten völkerrechtlichen Punkt „Selbstverteidigungsrecht“.

Israel ist eine Siedlerkolonie. Es ist kein Staat, dessen Staatsvolk dort schon länger lebte, sondern eines, das die vorhandene Bevölkerung in den letzten 100 Jahren stückweise verdrängt hat, und zwar nicht friedlich, sondern mit Gewalt.

Die Ansprüche der vorher ansässigen Bevölkerung, die 1947 nach Gaza geflohen ist, werden von vielen Leuten gern negiert.

👾 I don’t expect cis people to just sit there and take what sounds like direct threats of actionable violence (the thing against me was passive but the one against silvereagle was pretty fuckin egregious) from trans people just because we are oppressed by other cis people with way more power

what kind of expectation is that?

we don’t do that, I don’t remember any time anyone on our side ever did such a thing, and we wouldn’t tolerate open threats of violence like that especially against a Black person

the goalposts are so weirdly misaligned on this field, that a trans woman criticizing Ro even mildly is considered harassment or even “violence”, but “I know where you live and I will come there and show you terror” (paraphrase) is totally fine and justified in response to someone sharing some mistaken info that didn’t hurt anyone

Das, was zur Hamas zu sagen ist, ist, dass Israels Hardliner mehrmals darum bemüht haben, die zu stärken: Insbesondere in der ersten Intifada, und 2006, jeweils, um die PLO zu schwächen. An der Existenz der Hamas sind Israels Hardliner so schuldig, dass sie auch für deren Terror in Regress genommen werden müssen.

Für die Hardliner Israels ist es wichtig, dass die Hamas Positionen vertritt, über die nicht verhandelt werden kann: Die wollen ja auch nicht verhandeln.

Hoy mientras paseaba a mis perritos me di cuenta de algo.

Esta mal llamarle pet projects, porque a un pet no lo matas cuando no funciona, un proyecto de software es una responsabilidad. Deberiamos usar otro nombre mas apropiado.
También creo que hay gente que no deberia estar desarrollando cierto tipo de software. Peor aun administrando su desarrollo. Peor aun, vendiendolo.

El otro día leí de alguien que por su trabajo había quedado con dolor y ansiedad. Lo entiendo totalmente.

Hay proyectos que luego son tan criticos pero tan mal planeados que se vuelve estresante trabajarlos. Horas extra, pagos nulos. Amenazas constantes. Uno ya no esta tranquilo por entrar a llamadas con esa gente.

Hace unos dias estaba pensando que incluso el termino de software como producto esta mal. Un proyecto de software es un compromiso a largo plazo que no se termina cuando se entrega. Pero poca gente entiende esto, por eso digo que no deberian administrar o venderlo si no entienden.

Me encanta desarrollar software. Me encanta aprender sobre temas que conllevan su desarrollo y mantenimiento y puesta en marcha. Me encanta solucionar problemas para el usuario. Creo en el poder y soluciones que provee el software, la web y la Internet. Pero en un punto perdimos el rumbo.

Y creo que mejores formas son posibles. Por los comentarios que veo en redes sociales, por las cosas que dicen algunas personas que admiro.

Un mejor ambiente de desarrollo de software es posible. Lo se. Pero por eso hay que quitar a esas personas que lo hacen imposible.
Descargo de responsabilidades, no me estoy refiriendo a ninguna persona, empresa u organización en especifico con estas publicaciones. Es algo general y común en la industria y por eso lo comento.

I feel like I should document my recovery, since people doing so helped me a lot.

I had surgery yesterday morning. I got wheeled back into the OR about 22ish hours ago.

I was worried about getting sleep last night. But that went really well. I'm basically just up early because I'm just like, excited. Lol

The pain in my inguinal canals is barely present now, even though that was the thing that was basically bugging me the most yesterday. Maybe it will come back again after I'm sitting up and moving around today.

I've only been taking Tylenol (acetaminophen/paracetamol) for pain since the hospital. They gave me tramadol but I doubt I'll need it.

Also, I've been hearing a lot about post-surgery nausea. I didn't have that problem almost at all. Just this lingering icky burp feeling occasionally during recovery at the hospital.

They offered me Ativan (Lorazepam) before surgery. I told them I heard anxiety meds increase recovery time, they said that wouldn't be an issue. Since I was starting to feel anxious I took it. It helped.

Also I guess I was intubated during surgery. That was kind of scary, but I don't remember the breathing tube at all. My throat was a bit irritated after surgery. It feels fine today.

But the legislature sued to intervene and get the case re-heard. Again.

State court granted the appeal and will re-hear the case, even though nothing about the facts or law has changed significantly since last year's decision.

The kicker: The opinion is written by the son of the state Senate Majority Leader.

Who has never recused himself for a damned thing involving his father.

(Side note: The 2023 court has done this before, notably in gerrrymandering cases.)
